         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers2211">
               <p>Wheatley became a <seg ana="itinerancy">traveling Methodist
                     preacher</seg> about <date when="1742">1742</date>, and attended the <date
                     when="1745">1745</date> Conference. While <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> initially thought highly of
                  him, doubts began to surface in <date when="1749">1749</date>. In <date
                     when="1751">1751</date>
                  <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> and <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName> expelled
                     <persName>Wheatley</persName> from the connexion in light of evidence of sexual
                  improprieties with young women in his circuit. Wheatley
                  immediately set up as an independent preacher in <placeName>Norwich</placeName>,
                  where he gathered a significant following, but soon fell into his former ways and
                  by <date when="1756">1756</date> had been found guilty of immorality in public
                  court. His reputation hampered the Methodist society in
                     <placeName>Norwich</placeName> for some time, even though he had been put out.
                  See Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 488–91; Pawson, <hi rend="italic"
                     >Letters</hi>, 3:142; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>,
                  390–91.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
